{"title_page": "Cistanthe guadalupensis", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|image = \n|genus = Cistanthe\n|species = guadalupensis\n|authority = ([[William Russel Dudley|Dudley]]) Carolin ex M.A. Hershkovitz\n|synonyms = ''Talinum guadalupense''\n}}\n\n'''''Cistanthe guadalupensis''''' is a species of flowering plant in the family [[Montiaceae]].<ref name = \"C132\">Carolin ex M.A. Hershkovitz, 1990 ''In: Phytologia, 68(4): 269''</ref> The plant is native to [[Guadalupe Island]].<ref name = \"source\">[http://www.plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:274693-2 World Plants: Synonymic Checklists of the Vascular Plants of the World]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q17244969}}\n\n[[Category:Cistanthe|guadalupensis]]\n[[Category:Flora of Baja California]]\n[[Category:Flora of Mexican Pacific Islands]]\n\n\n{{Caryophyllales-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|image = \n|genus = Cistanthe\n|species = guadalupensis\n|authority = ([[William Russel Dudley|Dudley]]) Carolin ex M.A. Hershkovitz\n|synonyms = ''Talinum guadalupense''\n}}\n\n'''''Cistanthe guadalupensis''''' is a species of flowering plant in the [[Montiaceae]] family.<ref name = \"C132\">Carolin ex M.A. Hershkovitz, 1990 ''In: Phytologia, 68(4): 269''</ref> The plant is native to [[Guadalupe Island]].<ref name = \"source\">[http://www.plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:274693-2 World Plants: Synonymic Checklists of the Vascular Plants of the World]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cistanthe|guadalupensis]]\n[[Category:Flora of Baja California]]\n[[Category:Flora of Mexican Pacific Islands]]\n\n{{Caryophyllales-stub}}{{Taxonbar|from=Q17244969}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cistanthe_guadalupensis"}
{"title_page": "Padayappa", "text_new": "{{short description|1999 film by K. S. Ravikumar}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Padayappa\n| image          = Padayappa.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[K. S. Ravikumar]]\n| producer       = K. Sathya Narayana<br />M. V. Krishna Rao<br />H. Vittal Prasad<br />[[P. L. Thenappan]]\n| writer         = K. S. Ravikumar\n| starring       = <!--do NOT bill Rajinikanth on top of Sivaji! This is how the credits begin!-->[[Sivaji Ganesan]]<br />[[Rajinikanth]]<br />[[Ramya Krishnan]]<br />[[Soundarya]]\n| music          = [[A. R. Rahman]]\n| cinematography = S. Murthy<br />Prasad\n| editing        = K. Thanigachalam\n| studio         = Arunachala Cine Creations\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1999|4|10}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n'''''Padayappa''''' is a 1999 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]], written and directed by [[K. S. Ravikumar]], and featuring [[Sivaji Ganesan]], [[Rajinikanth]], [[Ramya Krishnan]] and [[Soundarya]] in the lead roles, with [[Abbas (actor)|Abbas]], [[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]], [[Radha Ravi]] and [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] in supporting roles. The [[soundtrack album]] and [[background music|background score]] were composed by [[A. R. Rahman]].Initially, this movie was given to Vijay. But due to some reasons, Vijay rejected the offer.\n\nThe plot revolves around Padayappa (Rajinikanth), an engineer whose father (Sivaji Ganesan) dies of shock soon after he is defrauded and loses his property to his foster brother ([[Manivannan]]). Neelambari (Ramya Krishnan) initially loves Padayappa, but plans to take revenge on him and his love interest Vasundhara (Soundarya) after his family humiliates her father (Radha Ravi). The rest of the story deals with Padayappa climbing back to financial success and arranging his daughters' marriage while overcoming all the obstacles placed by Neelambari.\n\nPrincipal photography for the film began in October 1998. ''Padayappa'' was released on 10 April 1999 on the eve of [[Puthandu|Tamil New Year's Day]]. This was the first Tamil film to be released worldwide with 210 [[Publishing|prints]] and 700,000 audio cassettes. It became [[Tamil cinema]]'s highest-grossing film at that point. Ramya Krishnan's performance was praised, winning her a [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Award]] under the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil|Best Actress]] category. The film also won five [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]].\n\n== Plot ==\nPadayappa is a mechanical engineer who returns to his village after three years to attend his sister's wedding. Padayappa's family have been the richest landlords of their village and chieftains for their region. Padayappa's great grandfather had decreed all Hindu marriages in their region must take place in the Murugan temple, after the chieftain has verbally confirmed the consent from bride and groom. This tradition has been followed for 100 years and now Padayappa's father is the chieftain. Padayappa's younger sister is engaged to their maternal cousin Suryaprakash. During his stay, he comes across Vasundhara, and falls in love with her. However, shyness and fear of Neelambari whose family employs her and her mother as servants, prevents Vasundhara from initially expressing her feelings. Neelambari is Suryaprakash's spoilt US-returned sister who also loves Padayappa.\n\nUnexpectedly, Padayappa's father's foster brother demands half share in the family property, citing Padayappa's father's donations to the poor are draining the family resources and he himself has three children to take care of. Padayappa's father abruptly refuses to divide the property and instead gives the entire property to his foster brother. This forces Padayappa's family to leave their home, to a plot of land bought using Padayappa's salary. Unable to bear this shock, Padayappa's father dies at the entrance of the house. Suryaprakash silently cancels his wedding with Padayappa's sister and marries the daughter of Padayappa's father's foster brother, who now owns the property of Padayappa's father.\n\nMeanwhile, Padayappa discovers that a hill on his newly purchased property is composed of solid [[granite]], which allows him to start a granite business, from which he becomes exponentially rich. He uses the money to help the poor in his village, and provide them jobs. As his business flourishes, his family is able to once again settle down. Padayappa assumes his father's position as the village chieftain, and his sister gets married to one of the engineers who work in his company. When Neelambari learns about Padayappa's love for Vasundhara, she becomes jealous of her, and her parents beg Padayappa's widowed mother to allow Neelambari to marry Padayappa. However, to everyone's surprise, Padayappa's mother humiliates Padayappa's maternal uncle in front of the entire village when she agrees to a marriage between Padayappa and Vasundhara with Vasundhara's mother, her brother's servant. Unable to bear the humiliation, Padayappa's maternal uncle commits suicide.\n\nWhen Neelambari tries to kill Vasundhara by letting a bull loose on her, Padayappa saves her. Neelambari tries to poison Vasundhara, which fails after a snake knocks down the milk she poisons. Afterwards, Padayappa and Vasundhara marry. After the wedding, Neelambari locks herself in a room in Suryaprakash's house, thinking only about Padayappa for 18 years, during which Suryaprakash becomes the state's home minister. In between, Padayappa finds his father's foster brother in trouble financially as he was pulled out of the family house by a financier Krishnasamy Mudaliar, from whom he had borrowed money on interest. Padayappa helps his father's foster brother, who in turn becomes indebted to him and seeks Padayappa's pardon for his misdeeds; Padayappa forgives him.\n\nNeelambari plans her revenge on Padayappa, now a father of two daughters. Suryaprakash also has a son, Chandru, who studies at the same college as Padayappa's elder daughter, Anitha. Neelambari advises Chandru to make Anitha fall in love with him. At the same time, Padayappa plans to get Anitha married to his sister's son. Neelambari, having made Chandru pretend to fall in love with Anitha, plans to humiliate Padayappa by making Anitha say that she does not wish to marry a groom of her parents' choice and that she is in love with someone else. At the marriage ceremony, after Anitha does what Neelambari told her, Padayappa makes an oath to unite Anitha with her lover by the next ''[[Muhurta]]'' day, or commit suicide. Padayappa discovers that Chandru really did fall in love with Anitha even though he was only initially pretending to do so on Neelambari's advise. When Padayappa takes Chandru and Anitha to the temple to get married, Neelambari and Suryaprakash give chase to stop them. Suryaprakash is killed in a car accident during the chase.\n\nArmed with a [[machine gun]], Neelambari reaches the temple where Chandru and Anitha are married. When she tries to kill Padayappa, he saves her life by preventing a bull from attacking her, while at the same time dodging the bullets she fires at him. Rather than live with the humiliation of knowing she was unsuccessful in avenging her father's death, as well as having her life saved by her enemy, Neelambari commits suicide, promising to take revenge on Padayappa in her next birth. Padayappa prays for her soul to be at peace and eventually attain salvation.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- In order of the film's opening credits -->\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Sivaji Ganesan]] as Padayappa's father\n* [[Rajinikanth]] as Aarupadayappan (Padayappa)\n* [[Ramya Krishnan]] as Neelambari\n* [[Soundarya]] as Vasundhara\n* [[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]] as Padayappa's mother\n* [[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]] as Padayappa's sister\n* [[Radha Ravi]] as Neelambari's father\n* [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] as Suryaprakash, Neelambari's brother<!-- https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/pdfplus/10.1086/692128 -->\n* [[Manivannan]] as Padayappa's father's foster brother\n* [[Senthil]] as Azhagesan\n* [[Abbas (actor)|Abbas]] as Chandraprakash aka Chandru\n* [[Preetha Vijayakumar|Preetha]] as Anitha\n* [[Anu Mohan (Tamil actor)|Anu Mohan]] as Chinnarasu\n* [[Ramesh Khanna]] as Murugesan\n* [[Vadivukkarasi]] as Vasundhara's mother\n* [[Sathyapriya]] as Neelambari's mother\n* [[Mansoor Ali Khan (actor)|Mansoor Ali Khan]] as Krishnasamy Mudaliar\n* [[Prakash Raj]] as Subramaniam\n* [[Vasu Vikram]] as Padayappa's cousin\n* [[Raja Ravindra]] as Padayappa's cousin\n* [[Lavanya (actress)|Lavanya]] as Suryaprakash's wife\n* [[Kanal Kannan]] as a farmer told by Neelambari to kill the snake\n* [[Mohan Raman]] as the lawyer\n* [[Ravi Raghavendra]] as Ravi Chellaiah\n* [[Kovai Senthil]] as a village man<!--https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/actor-kovai-senthil-passes-away-in-coimbatore/articleshow/65749144.cms-->\n* [[K. S. Ravikumar]] (special appearance in the song \"Kikku Yerudhey\")\n* [[Robo Shankar]] (uncredited role)\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\nIn September 1998, [[Rajinikanth]] announced his next project, titled ''Padayappa'', with [[K. S. Ravikumar]] as director.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=172}} The story of this film was taken in part from the historical Tamil novel, ''[[Ponniyin Selvan]]'', by [[Kalki Krishnamurthy]].{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=175}} The title ''Padayappa'' is a corruption of Aarupadayappa {{mdash}} a sobriquet for [[Kartikeya|Murugan]] and his [[Six Abodes of Murugan|six abodes]].<ref name=\"Sis\" /> The film was produced by K. Sathya Narayana, M. V. Krishna Rao, and H. Vittal Prasad under their production banner, Arunachala Cine Creations,<ref name=\"Ragavendra Kalyana Mandapam\" /> along with P. L. Thenappan as co-producer.<ref name=\"100 days ad\" /> Lalitha Mani was the choreographer for the song sequences.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/my-first-break-lalitha-mani/article3023609.ece |title=My first break&nbsp;\u2014 Lalitha Mani |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=28 November 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165620/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/my-first-break-lalitha-mani/article3023609.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> [[Jyothi Krishna (director)|Jyothi Krishna]], son of producer [[A. M. Rathnam]], was involved in the development of the film's script.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/lf/2003/12/28/stories/2003122808930200.htm |title=Filmmaker with a difference |last=Kamath |first=Sudhish |date=28 December 2003 |work=The Hindu |access-date=23 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223093128/http://www.thehindu.com/lf/2003/12/28/stories/2003122808930200.htm |archive-date=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\n{{quote box\n| quote = Today's audience expects novelty from film makers and stars. The success of [Neelambari] in ''Padayappa'' is an example of this. Action and reaction are the key factors for an artiste\u2019s success.\n| source =&nbsp;\u2013 Ramya Krishnan, in an interview with ''[[The Hindu]]'' in July 1999.<ref name=\"RK\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 30%\n}}\nRajinikanth was cast as the title character, a city-based engineer who returns to his ancestral village.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=172}} [[Ramya Krishnan]] was cast as Padayappa's cousin Neelambari.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|pp=172-173}} The character is based on Nandini, a vengeful woman in ''Ponniyin Selvan''.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=175}}<ref name=\"toi\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/movie-milestone-20-years-of-rajinikanths-padayappa/articleshow/68795621.cms |title=Movie Milestone: 20 years of Rajinikanth's Padayappa |last=Suganth |first=M. |date=10 April 2019 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=10 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410134111/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/movie-milestone-20-years-of-rajinikanths-padayappa/articleshow/68795621.cms? |archive-date=10 April 2019}}</ref> [[Meena (actress)|Meena]] and [[Nagma]] were earlier considered for the role.<ref name=\"toi\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/2005/10/02/stories/2005100215430400.htm |title=Rajni, Sivaji two of a kind, says Dasari |date=2 October 2005 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 April 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.li/rtz6i |archive-date=19 April 2018}}</ref> Ramya Krishnan said she accepted the role because \"it was opposite a superstar and that too the character was a negative one, no one was ready to do it, but I did it. I didn't have any second thoughts.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150717/entertainment-tollywood/article/rajamouli%E2%80%99s-story-gave-me-goosebumps-ramya-krishna |title=Rajamouli's story gave me goosebumps: Ramya Krishna |last=Kavirayani |first=Suresh |date=17 July 2015 |work=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |access-date=18 July 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718092552/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150717/entertainment-tollywood/article/rajamouli%E2%80%99s-story-gave-me-goosebumps-ramya-krishna |archive-date=18 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimran was considered for the role of Vasundhara, before the role went to [[Soundarya]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://m.rediff.com/movies/1998/aug/28ss.htm |title=Rajni returns! |last=Rajitha |date=28 August 1998 |website=Rediff.com |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165838/http://m.rediff.com/movies/1998/aug/28ss.htm |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> who had earlier worked with Rajinikanth in ''[[Arunachalam (film)|Arunachalam]]'' (1997).<ref name=\"RK\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/396667312D9B1C48652569400062A3BA |title=Glamour girl to star performer |last=Narasimhan |first=M. L. |date=2 July 1999 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152138/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/396667312D9B1C48652569400062A3BA |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> Ravikumar revealed that makers could not sign Simran due to her busy schedule and Meena was also considered for Vasundhara's role.<ref name=\"toi\" /> [[Shalini]] was touted to play the role of Padayappa's sister,<ref name=\"Sis\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1998/nov/03ss.htm |title=The sis image |last=Rajitha |date=3 November 1998 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165922/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1998/nov/03ss.htm |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=18 December 2014}}</ref> but the role eventually went to [[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/two-worlds-one-goal/article3021007.ece |title=Two worlds, one goal |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=9 January 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165433/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/two-worlds-one-goal/article3021007.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> [[Abbas (actor)|Abbas]] was cast as Chandru.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}}\n\nThe characterisation of the older Padayappa&nbsp;\u2014 bearded, with sunglasses&nbsp;\u2014 is based on Rajinikanth's look as the character Manik Baashha in ''[[Baashha]]'' (1995).{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}}<ref name=\"nadar\" /> Vijayakumar was the initial choice before [[Sivaji Ganesan]] was cast as Padayappa's father;{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}}<ref name=\"toi\" /> ''Padayappa'' was his penultimate release before ''[[Pooparika Varugirom]]'' (1999).{{sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|p=244}} His character's appearance, with a mutton-chop moustache, is based on a similar role he played in ''[[Thevar Magan]]'' (1992).{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}} [[Manivannan]] was cast as the foster brother of Ganesan's character.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jun/08sspice.htm |title=Manivannan on Rajnikanth |last=Nadar |first=Ganesh |date=8 June 2007 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005153243/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jun/08sspice.htm |archive-date=5 October 2017 |access-date=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Padayappa Swing Scene.jpg|thumb|The scene where Padayappa pulls down a swing for him to sit on was based on a sequence in the Indian epic ''[[Ramayana]]'', where the Hindu god [[Hanuman]] makes a chair for himself to sit on.<ref name=\"swingscene\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/k-s-ravikumar-on-his-recent-film-mudinja-ivana-pudi/article8985367.ece |title=Cinema is just business |last=Srinivasan |first=Sudhir |date=13 August 2016 |work=The Hindu |access-date=15 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815001757/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/k-s-ravikumar-on-his-recent-film-mudinja-ivana-pudi/article8985367.ece |archive-date=15 August 2016}}</ref>]]\n''Padayappa'' began [[principal photography]] at the Ragavendra Kalyana Mandapam on 1 October 1998.<ref name=\"Ragavendra Kalyana Mandapam\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/News/98/Nov/news1.htm |title=Tamil Movie News |last=Sandya |website=[[Ananda Vikatan]], [[Kumudam]], Cinema Express |publisher=Indolink |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170120/http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/News/98/Nov/news1.htm |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=18 December 2014}}</ref>{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=172}} The film's climax scene was one of the first to be shot,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrintGifMSIE_PASTISSUES2&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOICH/2011/04/08&ChunkNum=0&ID=Ar03403 |title=Did You Know? |date=8 April 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.li/175uP |archive-date=18 April 2018}}</ref> and was filmed in one take using two cameras. Around 2,000 extras were used for the scene.<ref name=\"RK\" /> The car that was used in the scene which introduced Neelambari in the film belonged to Ravikumar.<ref name=\"toi\" /> Ravikumar used the newly purchased car in the film at Rajinikanth's insistence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/did-you-know-/It-was-KS-Ravikumars-car-in-Padayappa/articleshow/31835057.cms |title=It was KS Ravikumar's car in Padayappa |date=6 March 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6UwRZEyRW?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/did-you-know-/It-was-KS-Ravikumars-car-in-Padayappa/articleshow/31835057.cms |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> Filming also took place in [[Mysore]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajini-starts-work-on-lingaa/article5971157.ece |title=Rajini starts work on Lingaa |date=3 May 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170617/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajini-starts-work-on-lingaa/article5971157.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> The [[Vadapalani]]-based shop, D. V. Nehru wigs, supplied the wigs that were sported by Ganesan in the film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/society/look-whats-receding/article4869415.ece |title=Look what's receding |last=Kannadasan |first=Akila |date=1 July 2013 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170659/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/society/look-whats-receding/article4869415.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> In an August 2016 interview with Sudhir Srinivasan of ''The Hindu'', Ravikumar mentioned that a scene where Padayappa uses his [[shawl]] to pull down a swing from the ceiling on which he sits after not being given a chair to sit by Neelambari, was inspired by a sequence in the Indian epic ''[[Ramayana]]''. The sequence features the Hindu god [[Hanuman]] making a seat using his tail after [[Ravana]], the [[Rakshasa|demon]] king of [[Lanka]], does not provide the former a chair to sit.<ref name=\"swingscene\" />\n\n\"Kikku Yerudhey\" was the last song sequence to be shot. For the sequence, Rajinikanth required Ravikumar to sport an outfit similar to Rajinikanth's, and enact a small part in the song. Rajinikanth also selected the part of the song where Ravikumar would make his appearance. After reluctantly agreeing to do the part, the sequence where they both appear together was filmed. Rajinikanth said he felt the shot did not look right, and re-takes for Ravikumar's sequence were done. After the re-takes were completed, Rajinikanth admitted that the first sequence was fine. When Ravikumar asked the cameraman why he had not told him earlier, the cameraman replied by saying that Rajinikanth wanted Ravikumar to do seven takes, to teach him a lesson for all the takes that Ravikumar had required of Rajinikanth.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2012|page=38}}\n\n== Themes ==\nWriting for ''[[PopMatters]]'', Ranjani Krishnakumar noted that ''Padayappa'' underlined Rajinikanth's political manoeuvres, evident when his character's lover sings \"''Kaadhal therdhalil kattil sinnathil vetri petru nee vaazgha''\" (In the election of love, with the symbol of bed, may you win and flourish).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/feature/tamil-film-mannan-presses-the-limits-of-using-violence-on-a-female-nemesis/ |title=Tamil Film 'Mannan' Presses the Limits of Using Violence on a Female Nemesis |last=Krishnakumar |first=Ranjani |date=24 April 2017 |website=[[PopMatters]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170506165125/http://www.popmatters.com/feature/tamil-film-mannan-presses-the-limits-of-using-violence-on-a-female-nemesis/ |archive-date=6 May 2017 |access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref><!-- https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/pdfplus/10.1086/692128 --><!-- https://www.thehindu.com/thread/arts-culture-society/a-look-back-at-rajinikanth-classic-padayappa-and-how-it-villainised-the-progressive-woman/article26943751.ece -->\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Padayappa (soundtrack)}}\n\nThe film's soundtrack and [[background music|background score]] were composed by A. R. Rahman, with lyrics by [[Vairamuthu]]. The soundtrack was released through Star Music.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/padayppa-original-motion-picture/id946197222 |title=Padayppa (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |publisher=[[iTunes]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219171116/https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/padayppa-original-motion-picture/id946197222 |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> Strips of herbal rejuvenator capsules were sold along with the film's music cassettes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jun/07ss.htm |title=Pep pills with ''Padayappa'' |last=Rajitha |date=7 June 1999 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226045726/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jun/07ss.htm |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref> Before the film's release, Rahman asked Ravikumar if the soundtrack could be released in August 1999. Ravikumar informed Rahman that he had already discussed a release date with the press, and that Rahman would be blamed for any delay. To make the deadline, Rahman did a live re-recording of both the soundtrack and score to finish them on time.{{Sfn|Mathai|2009|page=181}}\n\nThe credits for the song \"Vetri Kodi Kattu\", sung by Palakkad Sreeram, initially went to [[Malaysia Vasudevan]], who publicly stated that the credits for the song should have been attributed to Sreeram. Rahman requested the company who manufactured the audio cassettes to make the change.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/musical-notes/article2252968.ece |title=Musical notes |last=Pradeep |first=K |date=8 September 2007 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170952/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/musical-notes/article2252968.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> The song \"Minsara Kanna\" is based on the ''[[Vasantha (raga)|Vasantha]]'' [[raga]],<ref name=\"Charulatha\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/a-ragas-journey-hopeful-festive-vibrant-vasantha/article2780440.ece |title=A Raga's Journey&nbsp;\u2014 Hopeful, festive, vibrant Vasantha |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |date=6 January 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219171231/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/a-ragas-journey-hopeful-festive-vibrant-vasantha/article2780440.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014 |author-link=Charulatha Mani}}</ref> while \"Vetri Kodi Kattu\" is based on the ''[[Keeravani]]'' raga.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/harmonious-symmetry/article4657111.ece |title=Harmonious symmetry |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |date=26 April 2013 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219171338/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/harmonious-symmetry/article4657111.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> \"Minsara Kanna\" established [[Srinivas (singer)|Srinivas]] as a leading singer in the film industry.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/medicos-chill-out-as-srinivas-sings/article1903767.ece |title=Medicos chill out as Srinivas sings |last=Aishwarya |first=S. |date=3 September 2007 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226051029/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/medicos-chill-out-as-srinivas-sings/article1903767.ece |archive-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nSinger [[Charulatha Mani]], in her column for ''The Hindu'', \"A Raga's journey\", called \"Minsara Kanna\" a \"mind-blowing piece\".<ref name=\"Charulatha\" /> Srikanth Srinivasa of the ''[[Deccan Herald]]'' wrote, \"The music by [Rahman], to Vairamuthu\u2019s lyrics, sounds good while the movie is on, though whether without the presence of [Rajinikanth] they would have, is another thing.\"<ref name=\"Deccan Herald\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/384572F6661CE28265256941003DC8D3 |title=Reviews&nbsp;\u2014 Padayappa (Tamil) |last=Srinivasa |first=Srikanth |date=18 April 1999 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152101/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/384572F6661CE28265256941003DC8D3 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> S. Shiva Kumar of ''[[The Times of India]]'' was more critical of the soundtrack, and called it \"lacklustre\".<ref name=\"TOI\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/6A5D40A8C4F809FE65256941001E4B98 |title=Cinema&nbsp;\u2014 Padayappa |last=Kumar |first=S. Shiva |date=25 April 1999 |work=The Times of India |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152125/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/6A5D40A8C4F809FE65256941001E4B98 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n''Padayappa'' was released on 10 April 1999 on the eve of [[Puthandu|Tamil New Year's Day]].{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=175}} It was the first Tamil film to be released worldwide with over 200 prints, and 700,000 audio cassettes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/05495DEA90500B0B65256940004D0DE2 |title=Cos' fancy for Rajinikant |last=V |first=Balasubramanian |date=13 May 1999 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=26 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322151904/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/05495DEA90500B0B65256940004D0DE2 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> The film's rights in Japan were sold for US$50,000, which was the highest an Indian film fetched for commercial release in 1999.{{Sfn|Vasudevan|2011|page=336}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/3DCC69C3634728AB65256940006144AB |title=Rajni-starrer bowls over |date=30 June 1999 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=26 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152021/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/3DCC69C3634728AB65256940006144AB |archive-date=22 March 2012 |publisher=[[Indo-Asian News Service]]}}</ref> Co-producer Thenappan registered the film posters as a Class 34 trademark in 1998, to be used for trademarking such items as [[beedi]]s, cigarettes, [[cheroot]]s and tobacco, making it the first instance of brand extension in the Tamil film industry.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=205}} The pre-release business of the film's overseas rights amounted to {{INR}}30 million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-03-31/news/27363415_1_tamil-films-rajnikanth-film-film-baba |title=Bump and grind to a global tune |last=Govardan |first=D. |date=31 March 2002 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=27 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227040730/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-03-31/news/27363415_1_tamil-films-rajnikanth-film-film-baba |archive-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> According to an estimate by trade analyst Sreedhar Pillai, the value of the theatrical and satellite rights for ''Padayappa'' was approximately {{INR}}20 million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/tamil-film-distribution-outside-of-tamil-nadu-and-rest-of-india/article8455089.ece |title=Kollywood conquers the country |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=9 April 2016 |work=The Hindu |access-date=10 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410070751/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/tamil-film-distribution-outside-of-tamil-nadu-and-rest-of-india/article8455089.ece |archive-date=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''[[Ananda Vikatan]]'', in its original review of the film dated 25 April 1999, wrote that the original stamp of Rajinikanth style could be seen in the film several times, adding that Ramya Krishnan had matched Rajinikanth and created a royal path separately, and concluded that the film was exclusively made for Rajinikanth's fans, giving it a rating of 41 out of 100.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=25 April 1999 |title=\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bae\u0bcd: \u0baa\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe |trans-title=Movie Review: Padayappa |journal=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=Tamil}}</ref> Srikanth Srinivasa of ''Deccan Herald'' gave the film a positive verdict, claiming that the \"positive energy generated by this film is simply astounding\", and labelling Rajinikanth's role as \"terrific\".<ref name=\"Deccan Herald\" /> Ganesh Nadar of [[Rediff.com|Rediff]] also gave a positive review, praising Ramya Krishnan's performance in the film, and said that she \"does a fantastic job\", concluding, \"... if you are a Rajni fan, this film is vintage stuff.\"<ref name=\"nadar\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/apr/28pada.htm |title=Rajni does it again |last=Nadar |first=Ganesh |date=28 April 1999 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226055558/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/apr/28pada.htm |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nP. C. Balasubramanianram and N. Ramakrishnan, in their book, ''Grand Brand Rajini'', said, \"''Padayappa'', in one way, stands testimony to Rajini's life itself.\"{{Sfn|Balasubramanianram|Ramakrishnan|2012|page=112}} However, S. Shiva Kumar of ''The Times of India'' was critical of the film's allusions to the actor's political career, stating that the film was \"more style than substance\".<ref name=\"TOI\" /> [[Sify]] praised Ramya Krishnan's performance but criticised Rajinikanth, stating that he had nothing to do but \"be the Superman and spew dialogues\". The reviewer concluded, \"Technically the film has nothing much to offer.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/padaiappa-review-tamil-pcltPHgecjgij.html |title=Padaiappa |date=10 August 2001 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.li/RRm6L |archive-date=18 April 2018 |access-date=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\n''Padayappa'' was a box office success; T. R. Vivek of ''[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]'' says that the film was estimated to have earned {{INR}}440 million worldwide, with a total of {{INR}}380 million at the domestic box office, and {{INR}}60 million overseas.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archives.digitaltoday.in/businesstoday/20020915/features2.html |title=Superstar |last=Vivek |first=T. R. |date=15 September 2002 |website=[[Business Today (business magazine)|Business Today]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226075413/http://archives.digitaltoday.in/businesstoday/20020915/features2.html |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref> According to ''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]'', it was the highest grossing Tamil film at that point of time before being surpassed by another Rajinikanth film, ''[[Chandramukhi]]'' (2005),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050904/spectrum/main5.htm |title=The Rajni phenomenon |last=Chatterjee |first=Saibal |date=4 September 2005 |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |access-date=8 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608050503/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050904/spectrum/main5.htm |archive-date=8 June 2016}}</ref> although Rediff stated in 2014 that ''Padayappa''{{'s}} record was surpassed by ''[[Ghilli]]'' (2004).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/slide-show-1-the-top-7-vijay-movies-south/20140623.htm#4 |title=Looking at Vijay's TOP 7 landmark films |date=23 June 2014 |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |access-date=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film had a theatrical run of 100 days in 86 theatre centres,<ref name=\"100 days ad\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/CD6083CFAC6487EC6525693F001C8D43 |title=Padayappa |last=Anon |date=18 July 1999 |work=The Hindu |access-date=27 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322151945/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/CD6083CFAC6487EC6525693F001C8D43 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> and was dubbed into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] under the title ''Narasimha''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p-0pZiMoHSY |title=Narasimha Telugu Full Length Movie |date=5 September 2013 |publisher=Shalimar Telugu & Hindi Movies |access-date=29 July 2016}}</ref> The dubbed version was also a commercially successful venture, and had a theatrical run of 50 days in 49 theatres.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=205}}\n<!--== Scientific inaccuracies ==\nNikhil Talreja, an animal activist, criticised one scene from the film which shows a bull charging at Soundarya's character who is wearing a red sari. He accused the filmmakers of propagating the regressive myth that bulls charge at anything coloured red, noting that the creatures are actually [[Color blindness|colourblind]].<ref>http://www.cinemaexpress.com/stories/columns/2018/feb/28/busted-raising-a-red-flag-4799.html</ref> He criticised another scene propagating a similarly regressive myth, that snakes drink milk. He said, \"Snakes are not mammals. They are reptiles [...] They just don't drink milk.\"<ref>http://www.cinemaexpress.com/stories/columns/2018/jan/17/busted-milking-a-myth-4087.html</ref>\n-->\n\n== Accolades ==\nRamya Krishnan won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil|Best Actress]] at the [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]]. The film also won five [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]].<ref name=\"RK\" /><ref name=\"Dinakaran\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dinakaran.com/cinema/english/awards/29-12-00/state.htm |title=Tamilnadu Government Announces Cinema State Awards \u22121999 |website=[[Dinakaran]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010210034542/http://www.dinakaran.com/cinema/english/awards/29-12-00/state.htm |archive-date=10 February 2001 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Ceremony\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Outcome\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Filmfare Awards South]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|46th Filmfare Awards South\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil|Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil]]\n| Ramya Krishnan\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"RK\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|[[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"|Tamil Nadu State film Awards&nbsp;\u2013 1999\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] (first prize)\n| K. S. Ravikumar\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"5\" | <ref name=\"Dinakaran\" />\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Rajinikanth\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award Special Prize|Best Actress (Special Prize)]]\n| Ramya Krishnan\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Male Playback|Best Male Playback]]\n| [[Srinivas (singer)|Srinivas]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Make-up Artist|Best Make-up Artist]]\n| [[R. Sundaramoorthy|Sundaramoorthy]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n== Cancelled sequel ==\n''Padayappa''{{'}}s final cut initially lasted for 19 reels, which was considered too lengthy. Rather than cut the film, Rajinikanth suggested to Ravikumar to allot two [[intermission|intervals]]. He screened the uncut film for actor [[Kamal Haasan]], who told him not to go for two intervals. Haasan suggested ''Padayappa'' be edited in a way that would not disturb the storyline, so Ravikumar and the editor Thanigachalam managed to bring the film down to 14 reels.<ref name=\"toi\" /> When ''[[Kumudam]]''{{'}}s reporter Kannan learnt about the scenes which had been cut, he asked Rajinikanth to release them as ''Padayappa''{{'}}s sequel. Rajinikanth immediately spoke to Ravikumar about the possibility, but was informed that those reels had been destroyed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ssmusictheblog.blogspot.in/2013/11/the-reason-why-padayappa-part-2-was.html |title=The reason why Padayappa part 2 was dropped! |date=9 November 2013 |website=[[SS Music]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226122000/http://ssmusictheblog.blogspot.in/2013/11/the-reason-why-padayappa-part-2-was.html |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nWith the success of ''Padayappa'', Ramya Krishnan, who up to that point in time had only performed glamorous roles,<ref name=\"RK\" /> showed her versatility as an actress.<ref name=\"Punchnama\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajinikanths-punchnama/article5453029.ece |title=Rajinikanth's punchnama |date=13 December 2013 |work=The Hindu |access-date=27 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227082227/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajinikanths-punchnama/article5453029.ece |archive-date=27 December 2014 |publisher=Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> The character Neelambari reappears in ''[[Baba (2002 film)|Baba]]'' (2002), where she spots Baba (Rajinikanth) but sees him in her mind's eye in his Padayappa attire; she asks him the time. Her brother drags her away, and berates her for still not overcoming Padayappa. Ramya Krishnan and Nasser reprised their roles in this film.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=187}} The success of ''Padayappa'' led to a film being named after one of its songs, ''[[Minsara Kanna]]'' (1999), starring [[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]] with actress [[Kushboo]] appearing in a negative role similar to Ramya Krishnan's in ''Padayappa'';<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jul/26ss.htm |title=Ramya on a roll |last=Rajitha |date=26 July 1999 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227083410/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jul/26ss.htm |archive-date=27 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> another song from the film, ''[[Vetri Kodi Kattu]]'', became the name of a 2000 film directed by [[Cheran (director)|Cheran]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://m.rediff.com/movies/2000/jun/21spice.htm |title=Cheran movie shrouded in mystery |last=Rajitha |date=21 June 2000 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227083502/http://m.rediff.com/movies/2000/jun/21spice.htm |archive-date=27 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> Ramya Krishnan played the role of Malini in the film ''[[Arumugam (film)|Arumugam]]'' (2009), in which her character was similar to Neelambari.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/look-im-back/article18010.ece |title=Look, I'm Back! |last=Reddy |first=T. Krithika |date=10 September 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228042049/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/look-im-back/article18010.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/true-to-formula-arumugam/article660111.ece |title=True to formula&nbsp;\u2014 Arumugam |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=2 October 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228042226/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/true-to-formula-arumugam/article660111.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref> Ramya Krishnan's character in the television serial, ''Kalasam'', was also named Neelambari.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/the-arc-lights-beckon-again/article1435272.ece |title=The arc lights beckon again |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=15 August 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228042431/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/the-arc-lights-beckon-again/article1435272.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref> Actress [[Priyamani]], in an interview with Prathibha Joy of ''The Times of India'', stated her character in the [[Kannada]] film ''[[Ambareesha]]'' (2014), is similar to Neelambari.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/EXCLUSIVE-Priya-Mani-reveals-that-shes-in-a-relationship/articleshow/45191218.cms |title=Priya Mani reveals that she's in a relationship! |last=Joy |first=Prathibha |date=19 November 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120064038/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/EXCLUSIVE-Priya-Mani-reveals-that-shes-in-a-relationship/articleshow/45191218.cms |archive-date=20 November 2014}}</ref> In [[Chetan Bhagat]]'s novel, ''[[2 States: The Story of My Marriage]]'' (2009), when Krish Malhotra, the novel's protagonist, travels to [[Nungambakkam]] by [[auto rickshaw]], the auto rickshaw driver stops to worship a poster of ''Padayappa''.{{Sfn|Bhagat|2009|page=94}}\n\nSome of the quotes from the film that became popular were: \"En Vazhi Thani Vazhi.\" (My way is a unique way);<ref name=\"Punchnama\" /> \"Poda Andavane Namapakam Irukan\u2019\u2019 (God is on our side);<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment/11-life-transforming-quotes-superstar-rajinikanth/38444 |title=11 life transforming quotes from Superstar Rajinikanth |last=Nasreen |first=Raisa |date=24 April 2014 |publisher=Bookmyshow |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227111551/http://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment/11-life-transforming-quotes-superstar-rajinikanth/38444 |archive-date=27 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> \"Adhigama Aasaipadra Aambalaiyum, Adhigama Kobapadra Pombalaiyum, Nalla Vazhndhadha Sarithirame Kidaiyathu\" (There is no history of a man who desires too much or a woman who gets too angry living well), \"Kashtapadama Edhuvum Kidaikkathu. Kashtapadama Kidaikirathu Ennikkum Nilakkathu\" (One can gain nothing without working hard for it. That which is gained without hard work will not last forever);<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article481288.ece |title=Message through punchlines! |last=Kannath |first=Sruthi |date=8 August 2011 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107173921/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article481288.ece |archive-date=7 January 2015}}</ref> the English dialogue \"Anger is the cause of all miseries. One should know how to control it, otherwise life will become miserable\",{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=173}} and Neelambari's dialogue \"Vayasanalum un style um azhagum inum unna vitu pogala\" (Even though you have grown older, your style and beauty has not left you).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/tamil/happy-birthday-rajinikanth-4978398/ |title=Rajinikanth turns 67: From being a 'Sruthi Betham' to becoming a Superstar |date=12 December 2017 |website=The Indian Express |language=en-IN |access-date=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/petta-movie-review-rajinikanth-of-the-90s-returns-riding-this-karthik-subbaraj-time-machine/story-t7d69GyCdMUvlUuAWuMhDO.html |title=Petta movie review: Rajinikanth of the 90s returns, riding this Karthik Subbaraj time machine |date=10 January 2019 |website=Hindustan Times |access-date=15 April 2019}}</ref> One of Rajinikanth's climactic dialogues in the film {{mdash}} \"En Vazhi Thani Vazhi\" {{mdash}} was used as the title of a [[En Vazhi Thani Vazhi (2015 film)|2015 film]] directed by [[Shaji Kailas]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/south-follows-bollywood-popular-dialogues-songs-inspire-film-titles/story-u82HbSTtbLr5aruJkNh9vM.html |title=South follows Bollywood: Popular dialogues, songs inspire film titles |date=2 November 2014 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112182610/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/regional/south-follows-bollywood-popular-dialogues-songs-inspire-film-titles/article1-1281682.aspx |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> It was also used as the title of a 2010 book on [[Promotional merchandise|branding]] by Sridhar Ramanujam.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Branding-guru-and-columnist-Ramanujam-Sridhar-will-be-releasing-his-third-book-Enn-vazhi-Thani-Vazhi-tomorrow-evening-at-The-Spring-Hotel-in-Chennai-/articleshow/6677550.cms |title=Branding guru and columnist Ramanujam Sridhar will be releasing his third book, Enn vazhi Thani Vazhi, tomorrow evening at The Spring Hotel in Chennai. |last=Suganth |first=M. |date=3 October 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=10 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6get3M4IG?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Branding-guru-and-columnist-Ramanujam-Sridhar-will-be-releasing-his-third-book-Enn-vazhi-Thani-Vazhi-tomorrow-evening-at-The-Spring-Hotel-in-Chennai-/articleshow/6677550.cms |archive-date=10 April 2016}}</ref> Scenes and dialogues from the film were parodied in various other films, notable of which are ''[[Thirupathi Ezhumalai Venkatesa]]'' (1999),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Thirupathi Ezhumalai Venkatesa |type=motion picture |publisher=[[Thenandal Studio Limited|Sri Thenandal Films]] |time=10:06 to 10:34 |time-caption=From}}</ref> ''[[En Purushan Kuzhandhai Maadhiri]]'' (2001),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qJuvdinSDCc |title=En Purushan Kuzhandhai Maadhiri Comedy |date=7 November 2013 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=AP International |access-date=27 December 2014 |time=17:24}}</ref> ''[[Annai Kaligambal]]'' (2003),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Annai Kaligambal |date=2003 |last=[[Rama Narayanan]] (director) |publisher=[[Sri Thenandal Films]] |time=1:42:49 |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' (2007).<ref>''Sivaji'' (Blu-ray 1080p HD). Clip from 27:50 to 27:56.</ref> ''[[Vel (film)|Vel]]'' (2007),<ref>''Vel'' (DVD). Clip from 17:28 to 17:57.</ref> ''[[Siva Manasula Sakthi]]'' (2009),<ref>''Siva Manasula Sakthi'' (DVD). Clip from 56:05 to 56:53.</ref> ''[[Malai Malai]]'' (2009),<ref>''Malai Malai'' (DVD). Clip from 2:06:12 to 2:06:21.</ref> ''[[Vanakkam Chennai]]'' (2013),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Vanakkam Chennai |date=2013 |last=Kiruthiga Udhayanidhi (director) |publisher=Red Giant Movies |time=4:05 |medium=motion picture}}</ref>, ''[[All in All Azhagu Raja]]'' (2013) and ''[[Anbanavan Asaradhavan Adangadhavan]]'' (2017).<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=All in All Azhagu Raja |last=[[M. Rajesh]] (director) |publisher=[[Studio Green]] |time=2:04:06 to 2:04:36 |time-caption=From |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''Padayappa'' was also parodied in the [[Star Vijay]] comedy series [[Lollu Sabha]], in an episode appropriately named ''Vadayappa''.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Vadayappa |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mJ4THRS8swE |series=Lollu Sabha |network=[[Star Vijay]] |date=18 August 2004 |location=Chennai}}</ref>\n\nTo celebrate the 39th anniversary of Rajinikanth in the film industry, Digitally Inspired Media, a Chennai-based digital agency, made 39 posters of some of his films, in which ''Padayappa'' was included. The posters feature one \"punch\" line from the film, a representative image, and the year of the film's release.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/39-years-of-rajinikanths-career-superstar-minimalist-posters/article6350041.ece |title=Rajinikanth posters out on the Internet! |last=Lazarus |first=Susanne Myrtle |date=25 August 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228044809/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/39-years-of-rajinikanths-career-superstar-minimalist-posters/article6350041.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref> On Rajinikanth's 64th birthday, an agency named Minimal Kollywood Posters designed posters of Rajinikanth's films, in which the [[Minions (Despicable Me)|Minion]] characters from the ''[[Despicable Me (franchise)|Despicable Me]]'' franchise are dressed as Rajinikanth.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> The digital art was hand drawn on a digital pad by Gautham Raj.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> One of the posters depicted a minion sitting on a swing and dressed like Rajinikanth's character in ''Padayappa'', reminiscent of the swing scene.<ref name=\"Minions\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519501.cms |title=Superstar Rajinikanth as Minions&nbsp;\u2014 Padayappa (1999) |last=Prasad |first=Shiva |date=15 December 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6V9MjqjaU?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519501.cms |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SaabAwAAQBAJ |title=Grand Brand Rajini |last=Balasubramanianram |first=P. C. |last2=Ramakrishnan |first2=N. |publisher=Rupa Publications |year=2012 |isbn=978-81-2912-059-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AsNSz-1gUcMC |title=2 States: The Story of My Marriage |last=Bhagat |first=Chetan |publisher=Sandesh S. |year=2009 |isbn=978-81-291-1530-0 |ref=harv |author-link=Chetan Bhagat}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dhananjayan |first=G. |authorlink=G. Dhananjayan |title=The Best of Tamil Cinema, 1931 to 2010: 1977\u20132010 |chapter=Padayappa |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t6CGLgEACAAJ |year=2011 |publisher=Galatta Media |isbn=978-81-921043-0-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Autobiography of an Actor: Sivaji Ganesan, October 1928&nbsp;\u2013 July 2001 |title-link=Autobiography of an Actor |last=Ganesan |first=Sivaji |last2=Narayana Swamy |first2=T.S. |publisher=Sivaji Prabhu Charities Trust |year=2007 |ref=harv |author-link=Sivaji Ganesan}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gfCTmjEAChIC |title=A.R. Rahman: The Musical Storm |last=Mathai |first=Kamini |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-670-08371-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YyFMAgAAQBAJ |title=Rajinikanth 12.12.12: A Birthday Special |publisher=[[The Hindu|Kasturi & Sons Ltd]] |year=2012 |editor-last=Ramachandran |editor-first=Naman |editor-link=Naman Ramachandran |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |title-link=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |last=Ramachandran |first=Naman |publisher=Penguin Books |year=2014 |isbn=978-81-8475-796-5 |ref=harv |orig-year=2012}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kXfFAAAAQBAJ |title=The Melodramatic Public: Film Form and Spectatorship in Indian Cinema |last=Vasudevan |first=Ravi |date=2011 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |isbn=978-0-230-24764-2 |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|0213969}}\n\n{{K. S. Ravikumar}}\n{{TamilNaduStateFilmAwardBestFilm}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|1990s|India}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by K. S. Ravikumar]]\n[[Category:Indian films about revenge]]\n[[Category:Films scored by A. R. Rahman]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Indian family films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1999 film by K. S. Ravikumar}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Padayappa\n| image          = Padayappa.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[K. S. Ravikumar]]\n| producer       = K. Sathya Narayana<br />M. V. Krishna Rao<br />H. Vittal Prasad<br />[[P. L. Thenappan]]\n| writer         = K. S. Ravikumar\n| starring       = <!--do NOT bill Rajinikanth on top of Sivaji! This is how the credits begin!-->[[Sivaji Ganesan]]<br />[[Rajinikanth]]<br />[[Ramya Krishnan]]<br />[[Soundarya]]\n| music          = [[A. R. Rahman]]\n| cinematography = S. Murthy<br />Prasad\n| editing        = K. Thanigachalam\n| studio         = Arunachala Cine Creations\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1999|4|10}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil\n}}\n'''''Padayappa''''' is a 1999 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]], written and directed by [[K. S. Ravikumar]], and featuring [[Sivaji Ganesan]], [[Rajinikanth]], [[Ramya Krishnan]] and [[Soundarya]] in the lead roles, with [[Abbas (actor)|Abbas]], [[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]], [[Radha Ravi]] and [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] in supporting roles. The [[soundtrack album]] and [[background music|background score]] were composed by [[A. R. Rahman]].\n\nThe plot revolves around Padayappa (Rajinikanth), an engineer whose father (Sivaji Ganesan) dies of shock soon after he is defrauded and loses his property to his foster brother ([[Manivannan]]). Neelambari (Ramya Krishnan) initially loves Padayappa, but plans to take revenge on him and his love interest Vasundhara (Soundarya) after his family humiliates her father (Radha Ravi). The rest of the story deals with Padayappa climbing back to financial success and arranging his daughters' marriage while overcoming all the obstacles placed by Neelambari.\n\nPrincipal photography for the film began in October 1998. ''Padayappa'' was released on 10 April 1999 on the eve of [[Puthandu|Tamil New Year's Day]]. This was the first Tamil film to be released worldwide with 210 [[Publishing|prints]] and 700,000 audio cassettes. It became [[Tamil cinema]]'s highest-grossing film at that point. Ramya Krishnan's performance was praised, winning her a [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Award]] under the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil|Best Actress]] category. The film also won five [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]].\n\n== Plot ==\nPadayappa is a mechanical engineer who returns to his village after three years to attend his sister's wedding. Padayappa's family have been the richest landlords of their village and chieftains for their region. Padayappa's great grandfather had decreed all Hindu marriages in their region must take place in the Murugan temple, after the chieftain has verbally confirmed the consent from bride and groom. This tradition has been followed for 100 years and now Padayappa's father is the chieftain. Padayappa's younger sister is engaged to their maternal cousin Suryaprakash. During his stay, he comes across Vasundhara, and falls in love with her. However, shyness and fear of Neelambari whose family employs her and her mother as servants, prevents Vasundhara from initially expressing her feelings. Neelambari is Suryaprakash's spoilt US-returned sister who also loves Padayappa.\n\nUnexpectedly, Padayappa's father's foster brother demands half share in the family property, citing Padayappa's father's donations to the poor are draining the family resources and he himself has three children to take care of. Padayappa's father abruptly refuses to divide the property and instead gives the entire property to his foster brother. This forces Padayappa's family to leave their home, to a plot of land bought using Padayappa's salary. Unable to bear this shock, Padayappa's father dies at the entrance of the house. Suryaprakash silently cancels his wedding with Padayappa's sister and marries the daughter of Padayappa's father's foster brother, who now owns the property of Padayappa's father.\n\nMeanwhile, Padayappa discovers that a hill on his newly purchased property is composed of solid [[granite]], which allows him to start a granite business, from which he becomes exponentially rich. He uses the money to help the poor in his village, and provide them jobs. As his business flourishes, his family is able to once again settle down. Padayappa assumes his father's position as the village chieftain, and his sister gets married to one of the engineers who work in his company. When Neelambari learns about Padayappa's love for Vasundhara, she becomes jealous of her, and her parents beg Padayappa's widowed mother to allow Neelambari to marry Padayappa. However, to everyone's surprise, Padayappa's mother humiliates Padayappa's maternal uncle in front of the entire village when she agrees to a marriage between Padayappa and Vasundhara with Vasundhara's mother, her brother's servant. Unable to bear the humiliation, Padayappa's maternal uncle commits suicide.\n\nWhen Neelambari tries to kill Vasundhara by letting a bull loose on her, Padayappa saves her. Neelambari tries to poison Vasundhara, which fails after a snake knocks down the milk she poisons. Afterwards, Padayappa and Vasundhara marry. After the wedding, Neelambari locks herself in a room in Suryaprakash's house, thinking only about Padayappa for 18 years, during which Suryaprakash becomes the state's home minister. In between, Padayappa finds his father's foster brother in trouble financially as he was pulled out of the family house by a financier Krishnasamy Mudaliar, from whom he had borrowed money on interest. Padayappa helps his father's foster brother, who in turn becomes indebted to him and seeks Padayappa's pardon for his misdeeds; Padayappa forgives him.\n\nNeelambari plans her revenge on Padayappa, now a father of two daughters. Suryaprakash also has a son, Chandru, who studies at the same college as Padayappa's elder daughter, Anitha. Neelambari advises Chandru to make Anitha fall in love with him. At the same time, Padayappa plans to get Anitha married to his sister's son. Neelambari, having made Chandru pretend to fall in love with Anitha, plans to humiliate Padayappa by making Anitha say that she does not wish to marry a groom of her parents' choice and that she is in love with someone else. At the marriage ceremony, after Anitha does what Neelambari told her, Padayappa makes an oath to unite Anitha with her lover by the next ''[[Muhurta]]'' day, or commit suicide. Padayappa discovers that Chandru really did fall in love with Anitha even though he was only initially pretending to do so on Neelambari's advise. When Padayappa takes Chandru and Anitha to the temple to get married, Neelambari and Suryaprakash give chase to stop them. Suryaprakash is killed in a car accident during the chase.\n\nArmed with a [[machine gun]], Neelambari reaches the temple where Chandru and Anitha are married. When she tries to kill Padayappa, he saves her life by preventing a bull from attacking her, while at the same time dodging the bullets she fires at him. Rather than live with the humiliation of knowing she was unsuccessful in avenging her father's death, as well as having her life saved by her enemy, Neelambari commits suicide, promising to take revenge on Padayappa in her next birth. Padayappa prays for her soul to be at peace and eventually attain salvation.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- In order of the film's opening credits -->\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Sivaji Ganesan]] as Padayappa's father\n* [[Rajinikanth]] as Aarupadayappan (Padayappa)\n* [[Ramya Krishnan]] as Neelambari\n* [[Soundarya]] as Vasundhara\n* [[Lakshmi (actress)|Lakshmi]] as Padayappa's mother\n* [[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]] as Padayappa's sister\n* [[Radha Ravi]] as Neelambari's father\n* [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] as Suryaprakash, Neelambari's brother<!-- https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/pdfplus/10.1086/692128 -->\n* [[Manivannan]] as Padayappa's father's foster brother\n* [[Senthil]] as Azhagesan\n* [[Abbas (actor)|Abbas]] as Chandraprakash aka Chandru\n* [[Preetha Vijayakumar|Preetha]] as Anitha\n* [[Anu Mohan (Tamil actor)|Anu Mohan]] as Chinnarasu\n* [[Ramesh Khanna]] as Murugesan\n* [[Vadivukkarasi]] as Vasundhara's mother\n* [[Sathyapriya]] as Neelambari's mother\n* [[Mansoor Ali Khan (actor)|Mansoor Ali Khan]] as Krishnasamy Mudaliar\n* [[Prakash Raj]] as Subramaniam\n* [[Vasu Vikram]] as Padayappa's cousin\n* [[Raja Ravindra]] as Padayappa's cousin\n* [[Lavanya (actress)|Lavanya]] as Suryaprakash's wife\n* [[Kanal Kannan]] as a farmer told by Neelambari to kill the snake\n* [[Mohan Raman]] as the lawyer\n* [[Ravi Raghavendra]] as Ravi Chellaiah\n* [[Kovai Senthil]] as a village man<!--https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/actor-kovai-senthil-passes-away-in-coimbatore/articleshow/65749144.cms-->\n* [[K. S. Ravikumar]] (special appearance in the song \"Kikku Yerudhey\")\n* [[Robo Shankar]] (uncredited role)\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n=== Development ===\nIn September 1998, [[Rajinikanth]] announced his next project, titled ''Padayappa'', with [[K. S. Ravikumar]] as director.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=172}} The story of this film was taken in part from the historical Tamil novel, ''[[Ponniyin Selvan]]'', by [[Kalki Krishnamurthy]].{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=175}} The title ''Padayappa'' is a corruption of Aarupadayappa {{mdash}} a sobriquet for [[Kartikeya|Murugan]] and his [[Six Abodes of Murugan|six abodes]].<ref name=\"Sis\" /> The film was produced by K. Sathya Narayana, M. V. Krishna Rao, and H. Vittal Prasad under their production banner, Arunachala Cine Creations,<ref name=\"Ragavendra Kalyana Mandapam\" /> along with P. L. Thenappan as co-producer.<ref name=\"100 days ad\" /> Lalitha Mani was the choreographer for the song sequences.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/my-first-break-lalitha-mani/article3023609.ece |title=My first break&nbsp;\u2014 Lalitha Mani |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=28 November 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165620/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/my-first-break-lalitha-mani/article3023609.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> [[Jyothi Krishna (director)|Jyothi Krishna]], son of producer [[A. M. Rathnam]], was involved in the development of the film's script.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/lf/2003/12/28/stories/2003122808930200.htm |title=Filmmaker with a difference |last=Kamath |first=Sudhish |date=28 December 2003 |work=The Hindu |access-date=23 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223093128/http://www.thehindu.com/lf/2003/12/28/stories/2003122808930200.htm |archive-date=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\n{{quote box\n| quote = Today's audience expects novelty from film makers and stars. The success of [Neelambari] in ''Padayappa'' is an example of this. Action and reaction are the key factors for an artiste\u2019s success.\n| source =&nbsp;\u2013 Ramya Krishnan, in an interview with ''[[The Hindu]]'' in July 1999.<ref name=\"RK\" />\n| align = right\n| width = 30%\n}}\nRajinikanth was cast as the title character, a city-based engineer who returns to his ancestral village.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=172}} [[Ramya Krishnan]] was cast as Padayappa's cousin Neelambari.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|pp=172-173}} The character is based on Nandini, a vengeful woman in ''Ponniyin Selvan''.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=175}}<ref name=\"toi\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/movie-milestone-20-years-of-rajinikanths-padayappa/articleshow/68795621.cms |title=Movie Milestone: 20 years of Rajinikanth's Padayappa |last=Suganth |first=M. |date=10 April 2019 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=10 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410134111/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/movie-milestone-20-years-of-rajinikanths-padayappa/articleshow/68795621.cms? |archive-date=10 April 2019}}</ref> [[Meena (actress)|Meena]] and [[Nagma]] were earlier considered for the role.<ref name=\"toi\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/2005/10/02/stories/2005100215430400.htm |title=Rajni, Sivaji two of a kind, says Dasari |date=2 October 2005 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 April 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.li/rtz6i |archive-date=19 April 2018}}</ref> Ramya Krishnan said she accepted the role because \"it was opposite a superstar and that too the character was a negative one, no one was ready to do it, but I did it. I didn't have any second thoughts.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150717/entertainment-tollywood/article/rajamouli%E2%80%99s-story-gave-me-goosebumps-ramya-krishna |title=Rajamouli's story gave me goosebumps: Ramya Krishna |last=Kavirayani |first=Suresh |date=17 July 2015 |work=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |access-date=18 July 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718092552/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/150717/entertainment-tollywood/article/rajamouli%E2%80%99s-story-gave-me-goosebumps-ramya-krishna |archive-date=18 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimran was considered for the role of Vasundhara, before the role went to [[Soundarya]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://m.rediff.com/movies/1998/aug/28ss.htm |title=Rajni returns! |last=Rajitha |date=28 August 1998 |website=Rediff.com |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165838/http://m.rediff.com/movies/1998/aug/28ss.htm |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> who had earlier worked with Rajinikanth in ''[[Arunachalam (film)|Arunachalam]]'' (1997).<ref name=\"RK\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/396667312D9B1C48652569400062A3BA |title=Glamour girl to star performer |last=Narasimhan |first=M. L. |date=2 July 1999 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152138/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/396667312D9B1C48652569400062A3BA |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> Ravikumar revealed that makers could not sign Simran due to her busy schedule and Meena was also considered for Vasundhara's role.<ref name=\"toi\" /> [[Shalini]] was touted to play the role of Padayappa's sister,<ref name=\"Sis\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1998/nov/03ss.htm |title=The sis image |last=Rajitha |date=3 November 1998 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165922/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1998/nov/03ss.htm |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=18 December 2014}}</ref> but the role eventually went to [[Sithara (actress)|Sithara]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/two-worlds-one-goal/article3021007.ece |title=Two worlds, one goal |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=9 January 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219165433/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/two-worlds-one-goal/article3021007.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> [[Abbas (actor)|Abbas]] was cast as Chandru.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}}\n\nThe characterisation of the older Padayappa&nbsp;\u2014 bearded, with sunglasses&nbsp;\u2014 is based on Rajinikanth's look as the character Manik Baashha in ''[[Baashha]]'' (1995).{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}}<ref name=\"nadar\" /> Vijayakumar was the initial choice before [[Sivaji Ganesan]] was cast as Padayappa's father;{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}}<ref name=\"toi\" /> ''Padayappa'' was his penultimate release before ''[[Pooparika Varugirom]]'' (1999).{{sfn|Ganesan|Narayana Swamy|2007|p=244}} His character's appearance, with a mutton-chop moustache, is based on a similar role he played in ''[[Thevar Magan]]'' (1992).{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=174}} [[Manivannan]] was cast as the foster brother of Ganesan's character.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jun/08sspice.htm |title=Manivannan on Rajnikanth |last=Nadar |first=Ganesh |date=8 June 2007 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005153243/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/jun/08sspice.htm |archive-date=5 October 2017 |access-date=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Padayappa Swing Scene.jpg|thumb|The scene where Padayappa pulls down a swing for him to sit on was based on a sequence in the Indian epic ''[[Ramayana]]'', where the Hindu god [[Hanuman]] makes a chair for himself to sit on.<ref name=\"swingscene\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/k-s-ravikumar-on-his-recent-film-mudinja-ivana-pudi/article8985367.ece |title=Cinema is just business |last=Srinivasan |first=Sudhir |date=13 August 2016 |work=The Hindu |access-date=15 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815001757/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/k-s-ravikumar-on-his-recent-film-mudinja-ivana-pudi/article8985367.ece |archive-date=15 August 2016}}</ref>]]\n''Padayappa'' began [[principal photography]] at the Ragavendra Kalyana Mandapam on 1 October 1998.<ref name=\"Ragavendra Kalyana Mandapam\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/News/98/Nov/news1.htm |title=Tamil Movie News |last=Sandya |website=[[Ananda Vikatan]], [[Kumudam]], Cinema Express |publisher=Indolink |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170120/http://www.indolink.com/tamil/cinema/News/98/Nov/news1.htm |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=18 December 2014}}</ref>{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=172}} The film's climax scene was one of the first to be shot,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrintGifMSIE_PASTISSUES2&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOICH/2011/04/08&ChunkNum=0&ID=Ar03403 |title=Did You Know? |date=8 April 2011 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=18 April 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.li/175uP |archive-date=18 April 2018}}</ref> and was filmed in one take using two cameras. Around 2,000 extras were used for the scene.<ref name=\"RK\" /> The car that was used in the scene which introduced Neelambari in the film belonged to Ravikumar.<ref name=\"toi\" /> Ravikumar used the newly purchased car in the film at Rajinikanth's insistence.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/did-you-know-/It-was-KS-Ravikumars-car-in-Padayappa/articleshow/31835057.cms |title=It was KS Ravikumar's car in Padayappa |date=6 March 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=18 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6UwRZEyRW?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/did-you-know-/It-was-KS-Ravikumars-car-in-Padayappa/articleshow/31835057.cms |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> Filming also took place in [[Mysore]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajini-starts-work-on-lingaa/article5971157.ece |title=Rajini starts work on Lingaa |date=3 May 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170617/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajini-starts-work-on-lingaa/article5971157.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> The [[Vadapalani]]-based shop, D. V. Nehru wigs, supplied the wigs that were sported by Ganesan in the film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/society/look-whats-receding/article4869415.ece |title=Look what's receding |last=Kannadasan |first=Akila |date=1 July 2013 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170659/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/society/look-whats-receding/article4869415.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> In an August 2016 interview with Sudhir Srinivasan of ''The Hindu'', Ravikumar mentioned that a scene where Padayappa uses his [[shawl]] to pull down a swing from the ceiling on which he sits after not being given a chair to sit by Neelambari, was inspired by a sequence in the Indian epic ''[[Ramayana]]''. The sequence features the Hindu god [[Hanuman]] making a seat using his tail after [[Ravana]], the [[Rakshasa|demon]] king of [[Lanka]], does not provide the former a chair to sit.<ref name=\"swingscene\" />\n\n\"Kikku Yerudhey\" was the last song sequence to be shot. For the sequence, Rajinikanth required Ravikumar to sport an outfit similar to Rajinikanth's, and enact a small part in the song. Rajinikanth also selected the part of the song where Ravikumar would make his appearance. After reluctantly agreeing to do the part, the sequence where they both appear together was filmed. Rajinikanth said he felt the shot did not look right, and re-takes for Ravikumar's sequence were done. After the re-takes were completed, Rajinikanth admitted that the first sequence was fine. When Ravikumar asked the cameraman why he had not told him earlier, the cameraman replied by saying that Rajinikanth wanted Ravikumar to do seven takes, to teach him a lesson for all the takes that Ravikumar had required of Rajinikanth.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2012|page=38}}\n\n== Themes ==\nWriting for ''[[PopMatters]]'', Ranjani Krishnakumar noted that ''Padayappa'' underlined Rajinikanth's political manoeuvres, evident when his character's lover sings \"''Kaadhal therdhalil kattil sinnathil vetri petru nee vaazgha''\" (In the election of love, with the symbol of bed, may you win and flourish).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/feature/tamil-film-mannan-presses-the-limits-of-using-violence-on-a-female-nemesis/ |title=Tamil Film 'Mannan' Presses the Limits of Using Violence on a Female Nemesis |last=Krishnakumar |first=Ranjani |date=24 April 2017 |website=[[PopMatters]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.is/20170506165125/http://www.popmatters.com/feature/tamil-film-mannan-presses-the-limits-of-using-violence-on-a-female-nemesis/ |archive-date=6 May 2017 |access-date=6 May 2017}}</ref><!-- https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/pdfplus/10.1086/692128 --><!-- https://www.thehindu.com/thread/arts-culture-society/a-look-back-at-rajinikanth-classic-padayappa-and-how-it-villainised-the-progressive-woman/article26943751.ece -->\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Padayappa (soundtrack)}}\n\nThe film's soundtrack and [[background music|background score]] were composed by A. R. Rahman, with lyrics by [[Vairamuthu]]. The soundtrack was released through Star Music.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/padayppa-original-motion-picture/id946197222 |title=Padayppa (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |publisher=[[iTunes]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219171116/https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/padayppa-original-motion-picture/id946197222 |archive-date=19 December 2014 |access-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> Strips of herbal rejuvenator capsules were sold along with the film's music cassettes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jun/07ss.htm |title=Pep pills with ''Padayappa'' |last=Rajitha |date=7 June 1999 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226045726/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jun/07ss.htm |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref> Before the film's release, Rahman asked Ravikumar if the soundtrack could be released in August 1999. Ravikumar informed Rahman that he had already discussed a release date with the press, and that Rahman would be blamed for any delay. To make the deadline, Rahman did a live re-recording of both the soundtrack and score to finish them on time.{{Sfn|Mathai|2009|page=181}}\n\nThe credits for the song \"Vetri Kodi Kattu\", sung by Palakkad Sreeram, initially went to [[Malaysia Vasudevan]], who publicly stated that the credits for the song should have been attributed to Sreeram. Rahman requested the company who manufactured the audio cassettes to make the change.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/musical-notes/article2252968.ece |title=Musical notes |last=Pradeep |first=K |date=8 September 2007 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219170952/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/musical-notes/article2252968.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> The song \"Minsara Kanna\" is based on the ''[[Vasantha (raga)|Vasantha]]'' [[raga]],<ref name=\"Charulatha\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/a-ragas-journey-hopeful-festive-vibrant-vasantha/article2780440.ece |title=A Raga's Journey&nbsp;\u2014 Hopeful, festive, vibrant Vasantha |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |date=6 January 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219171231/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/a-ragas-journey-hopeful-festive-vibrant-vasantha/article2780440.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014 |author-link=Charulatha Mani}}</ref> while \"Vetri Kodi Kattu\" is based on the ''[[Keeravani]]'' raga.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/harmonious-symmetry/article4657111.ece |title=Harmonious symmetry |last=Mani |first=Charulatha |date=26 April 2013 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219171338/http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/music/harmonious-symmetry/article4657111.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> \"Minsara Kanna\" established [[Srinivas (singer)|Srinivas]] as a leading singer in the film industry.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/medicos-chill-out-as-srinivas-sings/article1903767.ece |title=Medicos chill out as Srinivas sings |last=Aishwarya |first=S. |date=3 September 2007 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226051029/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/medicos-chill-out-as-srinivas-sings/article1903767.ece |archive-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nSinger [[Charulatha Mani]], in her column for ''The Hindu'', \"A Raga's journey\", called \"Minsara Kanna\" a \"mind-blowing piece\".<ref name=\"Charulatha\" /> Srikanth Srinivasa of the ''[[Deccan Herald]]'' wrote, \"The music by [Rahman], to Vairamuthu\u2019s lyrics, sounds good while the movie is on, though whether without the presence of [Rajinikanth] they would have, is another thing.\"<ref name=\"Deccan Herald\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/384572F6661CE28265256941003DC8D3 |title=Reviews&nbsp;\u2014 Padayappa (Tamil) |last=Srinivasa |first=Srikanth |date=18 April 1999 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152101/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/384572F6661CE28265256941003DC8D3 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> S. Shiva Kumar of ''[[The Times of India]]'' was more critical of the soundtrack, and called it \"lacklustre\".<ref name=\"TOI\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/6A5D40A8C4F809FE65256941001E4B98 |title=Cinema&nbsp;\u2014 Padayappa |last=Kumar |first=S. Shiva |date=25 April 1999 |work=The Times of India |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152125/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/6A5D40A8C4F809FE65256941001E4B98 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n''Padayappa'' was released on 10 April 1999 on the eve of [[Puthandu|Tamil New Year's Day]].{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=175}} It was the first Tamil film to be released worldwide with over 200 prints, and 700,000 audio cassettes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/05495DEA90500B0B65256940004D0DE2 |title=Cos' fancy for Rajinikant |last=V |first=Balasubramanian |date=13 May 1999 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=26 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322151904/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/05495DEA90500B0B65256940004D0DE2 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> The film's rights in Japan were sold for US$50,000, which was the highest an Indian film fetched for commercial release in 1999.{{Sfn|Vasudevan|2011|page=336}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/3DCC69C3634728AB65256940006144AB |title=Rajni-starrer bowls over |date=30 June 1999 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=26 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152021/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/3DCC69C3634728AB65256940006144AB |archive-date=22 March 2012 |publisher=[[Indo-Asian News Service]]}}</ref> Co-producer Thenappan registered the film posters as a Class 34 trademark in 1998, to be used for trademarking such items as [[beedi]]s, cigarettes, [[cheroot]]s and tobacco, making it the first instance of brand extension in the Tamil film industry.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=205}} The pre-release business of the film's overseas rights amounted to {{INR}}30 million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-03-31/news/27363415_1_tamil-films-rajnikanth-film-film-baba |title=Bump and grind to a global tune |last=Govardan |first=D. |date=31 March 2002 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=27 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227040730/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2002-03-31/news/27363415_1_tamil-films-rajnikanth-film-film-baba |archive-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> According to an estimate by trade analyst Sreedhar Pillai, the value of the theatrical and satellite rights for ''Padayappa'' was approximately {{INR}}20 million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/tamil-film-distribution-outside-of-tamil-nadu-and-rest-of-india/article8455089.ece |title=Kollywood conquers the country |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=9 April 2016 |work=The Hindu |access-date=10 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410070751/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/tamil-film-distribution-outside-of-tamil-nadu-and-rest-of-india/article8455089.ece |archive-date=10 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''[[Ananda Vikatan]]'', in its original review of the film dated 25 April 1999, wrote that the original stamp of Rajinikanth style could be seen in the film several times, adding that Ramya Krishnan had matched Rajinikanth and created a royal path separately, and concluded that the film was exclusively made for Rajinikanth's fans, giving it a rating of 41 out of 100.<ref>{{Cite journal |date=25 April 1999 |title=\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bbe \u0bb5\u0bbf\u0bae\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0ba9\u0bae\u0bcd: \u0baa\u0b9f\u0bc8\u0baf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe |trans-title=Movie Review: Padayappa |journal=[[Ananda Vikatan]] |language=Tamil}}</ref> Srikanth Srinivasa of ''Deccan Herald'' gave the film a positive verdict, claiming that the \"positive energy generated by this film is simply astounding\", and labelling Rajinikanth's role as \"terrific\".<ref name=\"Deccan Herald\" /> Ganesh Nadar of [[Rediff.com|Rediff]] also gave a positive review, praising Ramya Krishnan's performance in the film, and said that she \"does a fantastic job\", concluding, \"... if you are a Rajni fan, this film is vintage stuff.\"<ref name=\"nadar\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/apr/28pada.htm |title=Rajni does it again |last=Nadar |first=Ganesh |date=28 April 1999 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226055558/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/apr/28pada.htm |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nP. C. Balasubramanianram and N. Ramakrishnan, in their book, ''Grand Brand Rajini'', said, \"''Padayappa'', in one way, stands testimony to Rajini's life itself.\"{{Sfn|Balasubramanianram|Ramakrishnan|2012|page=112}} However, S. Shiva Kumar of ''The Times of India'' was critical of the film's allusions to the actor's political career, stating that the film was \"more style than substance\".<ref name=\"TOI\" /> [[Sify]] praised Ramya Krishnan's performance but criticised Rajinikanth, stating that he had nothing to do but \"be the Superman and spew dialogues\". The reviewer concluded, \"Technically the film has nothing much to offer.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/padaiappa-review-tamil-pcltPHgecjgij.html |title=Padaiappa |date=10 August 2001 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=http://archive.li/RRm6L |archive-date=18 April 2018 |access-date=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\n''Padayappa'' was a box office success; T. R. Vivek of ''[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]'' says that the film was estimated to have earned {{INR}}440 million worldwide, with a total of {{INR}}380 million at the domestic box office, and {{INR}}60 million overseas.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archives.digitaltoday.in/businesstoday/20020915/features2.html |title=Superstar |last=Vivek |first=T. R. |date=15 September 2002 |website=[[Business Today (business magazine)|Business Today]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226075413/http://archives.digitaltoday.in/businesstoday/20020915/features2.html |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref> According to ''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]'', it was the highest grossing Tamil film at that point of time before being surpassed by another Rajinikanth film, ''[[Chandramukhi]]'' (2005),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050904/spectrum/main5.htm |title=The Rajni phenomenon |last=Chatterjee |first=Saibal |date=4 September 2005 |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |access-date=8 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608050503/http://www.tribuneindia.com/2005/20050904/spectrum/main5.htm |archive-date=8 June 2016}}</ref> although Rediff stated in 2014 that ''Padayappa''{{'s}} record was surpassed by ''[[Ghilli]]'' (2004).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/slide-show-1-the-top-7-vijay-movies-south/20140623.htm#4 |title=Looking at Vijay's TOP 7 landmark films |date=23 June 2014 |publisher=[[Rediff.com]] |access-date=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe film had a theatrical run of 100 days in 86 theatre centres,<ref name=\"100 days ad\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/(docid)/CD6083CFAC6487EC6525693F001C8D43 |title=Padayappa |last=Anon |date=18 July 1999 |work=The Hindu |access-date=27 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322151945/http://www.cscsarchive.org:8081/MediaArchive/art.nsf/%28docid%29/CD6083CFAC6487EC6525693F001C8D43 |archive-date=22 March 2012}}</ref> and was dubbed into [[Telugu language|Telugu]] under the title ''Narasimha''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=p-0pZiMoHSY |title=Narasimha Telugu Full Length Movie |date=5 September 2013 |publisher=Shalimar Telugu & Hindi Movies |access-date=29 July 2016}}</ref> The dubbed version was also a commercially successful venture, and had a theatrical run of 50 days in 49 theatres.{{Sfn|Dhananjayan|2011|page=205}}\n<!--== Scientific inaccuracies ==\nNikhil Talreja, an animal activist, criticised one scene from the film which shows a bull charging at Soundarya's character who is wearing a red sari. He accused the filmmakers of propagating the regressive myth that bulls charge at anything coloured red, noting that the creatures are actually [[Color blindness|colourblind]].<ref>http://www.cinemaexpress.com/stories/columns/2018/feb/28/busted-raising-a-red-flag-4799.html</ref> He criticised another scene propagating a similarly regressive myth, that snakes drink milk. He said, \"Snakes are not mammals. They are reptiles [...] They just don't drink milk.\"<ref>http://www.cinemaexpress.com/stories/columns/2018/jan/17/busted-milking-a-myth-4087.html</ref>\n-->\n\n== Accolades ==\nRamya Krishnan won the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil|Best Actress]] at the [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]]. The film also won five [[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]].<ref name=\"RK\" /><ref name=\"Dinakaran\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.dinakaran.com/cinema/english/awards/29-12-00/state.htm |title=Tamilnadu Government Announces Cinema State Awards \u22121999 |website=[[Dinakaran]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010210034542/http://www.dinakaran.com/cinema/english/awards/29-12-00/state.htm |archive-date=10 February 2001 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Award\n! Ceremony\n! Category\n! Nominee(s)\n! Outcome\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|[[Filmfare Awards South]]\n| rowspan=\"1\"|46th Filmfare Awards South\n| [[Filmfare Award for Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil|Best Actress&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil]]\n| Ramya Krishnan\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"RK\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"|[[Tamil Nadu State Film Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"5\"|Tamil Nadu State film Awards&nbsp;\u2013 1999\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] (first prize)\n| K. S. Ravikumar\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"5\" | <ref name=\"Dinakaran\" />\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]\n| Rajinikanth\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award Special Prize|Best Actress (Special Prize)]]\n| Ramya Krishnan\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Male Playback|Best Male Playback]]\n| [[Srinivas (singer)|Srinivas]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu State Film Award for Best Make-up Artist|Best Make-up Artist]]\n| [[R. Sundaramoorthy|Sundaramoorthy]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n== Cancelled sequel ==\n''Padayappa''{{'}}s final cut initially lasted for 19 reels, which was considered too lengthy. Rather than cut the film, Rajinikanth suggested to Ravikumar to allot two [[intermission|intervals]]. He screened the uncut film for actor [[Kamal Haasan]], who told him not to go for two intervals. Haasan suggested ''Padayappa'' be edited in a way that would not disturb the storyline, so Ravikumar and the editor Thanigachalam managed to bring the film down to 14 reels.<ref name=\"toi\" /> When ''[[Kumudam]]''{{'}}s reporter Kannan learnt about the scenes which had been cut, he asked Rajinikanth to release them as ''Padayappa''{{'}}s sequel. Rajinikanth immediately spoke to Ravikumar about the possibility, but was informed that those reels had been destroyed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ssmusictheblog.blogspot.in/2013/11/the-reason-why-padayappa-part-2-was.html |title=The reason why Padayappa part 2 was dropped! |date=9 November 2013 |website=[[SS Music]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226122000/http://ssmusictheblog.blogspot.in/2013/11/the-reason-why-padayappa-part-2-was.html |archive-date=26 December 2014 |access-date=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nWith the success of ''Padayappa'', Ramya Krishnan, who up to that point in time had only performed glamorous roles,<ref name=\"RK\" /> showed her versatility as an actress.<ref name=\"Punchnama\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajinikanths-punchnama/article5453029.ece |title=Rajinikanth's punchnama |date=13 December 2013 |work=The Hindu |access-date=27 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227082227/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/rajinikanths-punchnama/article5453029.ece |archive-date=27 December 2014 |publisher=Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> The character Neelambari reappears in ''[[Baba (2002 film)|Baba]]'' (2002), where she spots Baba (Rajinikanth) but sees him in her mind's eye in his Padayappa attire; she asks him the time. Her brother drags her away, and berates her for still not overcoming Padayappa. Ramya Krishnan and Nasser reprised their roles in this film.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=187}} The success of ''Padayappa'' led to a film being named after one of its songs, ''[[Minsara Kanna]]'' (1999), starring [[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]] with actress [[Kushboo]] appearing in a negative role similar to Ramya Krishnan's in ''Padayappa'';<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jul/26ss.htm |title=Ramya on a roll |last=Rajitha |date=26 July 1999 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227083410/http://www.rediff.com/movies/1999/jul/26ss.htm |archive-date=27 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> another song from the film, ''[[Vetri Kodi Kattu]]'', became the name of a 2000 film directed by [[Cheran (director)|Cheran]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://m.rediff.com/movies/2000/jun/21spice.htm |title=Cheran movie shrouded in mystery |last=Rajitha |date=21 June 2000 |publisher=Rediff |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227083502/http://m.rediff.com/movies/2000/jun/21spice.htm |archive-date=27 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> Ramya Krishnan played the role of Malini in the film ''[[Arumugam (film)|Arumugam]]'' (2009), in which her character was similar to Neelambari.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/look-im-back/article18010.ece |title=Look, I'm Back! |last=Reddy |first=T. Krithika |date=10 September 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228042049/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/look-im-back/article18010.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/true-to-formula-arumugam/article660111.ece |title=True to formula&nbsp;\u2014 Arumugam |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=2 October 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228042226/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/true-to-formula-arumugam/article660111.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref> Ramya Krishnan's character in the television serial, ''Kalasam'', was also named Neelambari.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/the-arc-lights-beckon-again/article1435272.ece |title=The arc lights beckon again |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=15 August 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228042431/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/the-arc-lights-beckon-again/article1435272.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref> Actress [[Priyamani]], in an interview with Prathibha Joy of ''The Times of India'', stated her character in the [[Kannada]] film ''[[Ambareesha]]'' (2014), is similar to Neelambari.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/EXCLUSIVE-Priya-Mani-reveals-that-shes-in-a-relationship/articleshow/45191218.cms |title=Priya Mani reveals that she's in a relationship! |last=Joy |first=Prathibha |date=19 November 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141120064038/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/EXCLUSIVE-Priya-Mani-reveals-that-shes-in-a-relationship/articleshow/45191218.cms |archive-date=20 November 2014}}</ref> In [[Chetan Bhagat]]'s novel, ''[[2 States: The Story of My Marriage]]'' (2009), when Krish Malhotra, the novel's protagonist, travels to [[Nungambakkam]] by [[auto rickshaw]], the auto rickshaw driver stops to worship a poster of ''Padayappa''.{{Sfn|Bhagat|2009|page=94}}\n\nSome of the quotes from the film that became popular were: \"En Vazhi Thani Vazhi.\" (My way is a unique way);<ref name=\"Punchnama\" /> \"Poda Andavane Namapakam Irukan\u2019\u2019 (God is on our side);<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment/11-life-transforming-quotes-superstar-rajinikanth/38444 |title=11 life transforming quotes from Superstar Rajinikanth |last=Nasreen |first=Raisa |date=24 April 2014 |publisher=Bookmyshow |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227111551/http://in.bookmyshow.com/entertainment/11-life-transforming-quotes-superstar-rajinikanth/38444 |archive-date=27 December 2014 |access-date=27 December 2014}}</ref> \"Adhigama Aasaipadra Aambalaiyum, Adhigama Kobapadra Pombalaiyum, Nalla Vazhndhadha Sarithirame Kidaiyathu\" (There is no history of a man who desires too much or a woman who gets too angry living well), \"Kashtapadama Edhuvum Kidaikkathu. Kashtapadama Kidaikirathu Ennikkum Nilakkathu\" (One can gain nothing without working hard for it. That which is gained without hard work will not last forever);<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article481288.ece |title=Message through punchlines! |last=Kannath |first=Sruthi |date=8 August 2011 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=7 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107173921/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article481288.ece |archive-date=7 January 2015}}</ref> the English dialogue \"Anger is the cause of all miseries. One should know how to control it, otherwise life will become miserable\",{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=173}} and Neelambari's dialogue \"Vayasanalum un style um azhagum inum unna vitu pogala\" (Even though you have grown older, your style and beauty has not left you).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/tamil/happy-birthday-rajinikanth-4978398/ |title=Rajinikanth turns 67: From being a 'Sruthi Betham' to becoming a Superstar |date=12 December 2017 |website=The Indian Express |language=en-IN |access-date=15 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/petta-movie-review-rajinikanth-of-the-90s-returns-riding-this-karthik-subbaraj-time-machine/story-t7d69GyCdMUvlUuAWuMhDO.html |title=Petta movie review: Rajinikanth of the 90s returns, riding this Karthik Subbaraj time machine |date=10 January 2019 |website=Hindustan Times |access-date=15 April 2019}}</ref> One of Rajinikanth's climactic dialogues in the film {{mdash}} \"En Vazhi Thani Vazhi\" {{mdash}} was used as the title of a [[En Vazhi Thani Vazhi (2015 film)|2015 film]] directed by [[Shaji Kailas]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/south-follows-bollywood-popular-dialogues-songs-inspire-film-titles/story-u82HbSTtbLr5aruJkNh9vM.html |title=South follows Bollywood: Popular dialogues, songs inspire film titles |date=2 November 2014 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112182610/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/regional/south-follows-bollywood-popular-dialogues-songs-inspire-film-titles/article1-1281682.aspx |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Indo-Asian News Service}}</ref> It was also used as the title of a 2010 book on [[Promotional merchandise|branding]] by Sridhar Ramanujam.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Branding-guru-and-columnist-Ramanujam-Sridhar-will-be-releasing-his-third-book-Enn-vazhi-Thani-Vazhi-tomorrow-evening-at-The-Spring-Hotel-in-Chennai-/articleshow/6677550.cms |title=Branding guru and columnist Ramanujam Sridhar will be releasing his third book, Enn vazhi Thani Vazhi, tomorrow evening at The Spring Hotel in Chennai. |last=Suganth |first=M. |date=3 October 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=10 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6get3M4IG?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/Branding-guru-and-columnist-Ramanujam-Sridhar-will-be-releasing-his-third-book-Enn-vazhi-Thani-Vazhi-tomorrow-evening-at-The-Spring-Hotel-in-Chennai-/articleshow/6677550.cms |archive-date=10 April 2016}}</ref> Scenes and dialogues from the film were parodied in various other films, notable of which are ''[[Thirupathi Ezhumalai Venkatesa]]'' (1999),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Thirupathi Ezhumalai Venkatesa |type=motion picture |publisher=[[Thenandal Studio Limited|Sri Thenandal Films]] |time=10:06 to 10:34 |time-caption=From}}</ref> ''[[En Purushan Kuzhandhai Maadhiri]]'' (2001),<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qJuvdinSDCc |title=En Purushan Kuzhandhai Maadhiri Comedy |date=7 November 2013 |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=AP International |access-date=27 December 2014 |time=17:24}}</ref> ''[[Annai Kaligambal]]'' (2003),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Annai Kaligambal |date=2003 |last=[[Rama Narayanan]] (director) |publisher=[[Sri Thenandal Films]] |time=1:42:49 |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' (2007).<ref>''Sivaji'' (Blu-ray 1080p HD). Clip from 27:50 to 27:56.</ref> ''[[Vel (film)|Vel]]'' (2007),<ref>''Vel'' (DVD). Clip from 17:28 to 17:57.</ref> ''[[Siva Manasula Sakthi]]'' (2009),<ref>''Siva Manasula Sakthi'' (DVD). Clip from 56:05 to 56:53.</ref> ''[[Malai Malai]]'' (2009),<ref>''Malai Malai'' (DVD). Clip from 2:06:12 to 2:06:21.</ref> ''[[Vanakkam Chennai]]'' (2013),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Vanakkam Chennai |date=2013 |last=Kiruthiga Udhayanidhi (director) |publisher=Red Giant Movies |time=4:05 |medium=motion picture}}</ref>, ''[[All in All Azhagu Raja]]'' (2013) and ''[[Anbanavan Asaradhavan Adangadhavan]]'' (2017).<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=All in All Azhagu Raja |last=[[M. Rajesh]] (director) |publisher=[[Studio Green]] |time=2:04:06 to 2:04:36 |time-caption=From |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''Padayappa'' was also parodied in the [[Star Vijay]] comedy series [[Lollu Sabha]], in an episode appropriately named ''Vadayappa''.<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Vadayappa |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mJ4THRS8swE |series=Lollu Sabha |network=[[Star Vijay]] |date=18 August 2004 |location=Chennai}}</ref>\n\nTo celebrate the 39th anniversary of Rajinikanth in the film industry, Digitally Inspired Media, a Chennai-based digital agency, made 39 posters of some of his films, in which ''Padayappa'' was included. The posters feature one \"punch\" line from the film, a representative image, and the year of the film's release.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/39-years-of-rajinikanths-career-superstar-minimalist-posters/article6350041.ece |title=Rajinikanth posters out on the Internet! |last=Lazarus |first=Susanne Myrtle |date=25 August 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228044809/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/39-years-of-rajinikanths-career-superstar-minimalist-posters/article6350041.ece |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref> On Rajinikanth's 64th birthday, an agency named Minimal Kollywood Posters designed posters of Rajinikanth's films, in which the [[Minions (Despicable Me)|Minion]] characters from the ''[[Despicable Me (franchise)|Despicable Me]]'' franchise are dressed as Rajinikanth.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> The digital art was hand drawn on a digital pad by Gautham Raj.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> One of the posters depicted a minion sitting on a swing and dressed like Rajinikanth's character in ''Padayappa'', reminiscent of the swing scene.<ref name=\"Minions\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519501.cms |title=Superstar Rajinikanth as Minions&nbsp;\u2014 Padayappa (1999) |last=Prasad |first=Shiva |date=15 December 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=28 December 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6V9MjqjaU?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519501.cms |archive-date=28 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SaabAwAAQBAJ |title=Grand Brand Rajini |last=Balasubramanianram |first=P. C. |last2=Ramakrishnan |first2=N. |publisher=Rupa Publications |year=2012 |isbn=978-81-2912-059-5 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AsNSz-1gUcMC |title=2 States: The Story of My Marriage |last=Bhagat |first=Chetan |publisher=Sandesh S. |year=2009 |isbn=978-81-291-1530-0 |ref=harv |author-link=Chetan Bhagat}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dhananjayan |first=G. |authorlink=G. Dhananjayan |title=The Best of Tamil Cinema, 1931 to 2010: 1977\u20132010 |chapter=Padayappa |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t6CGLgEACAAJ |year=2011 |publisher=Galatta Media |isbn=978-81-921043-0-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Autobiography of an Actor: Sivaji Ganesan, October 1928&nbsp;\u2013 July 2001 |title-link=Autobiography of an Actor |last=Ganesan |first=Sivaji |last2=Narayana Swamy |first2=T.S. |publisher=Sivaji Prabhu Charities Trust |year=2007 |ref=harv |author-link=Sivaji Ganesan}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gfCTmjEAChIC |title=A.R. Rahman: The Musical Storm |last=Mathai |first=Kamini |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-670-08371-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YyFMAgAAQBAJ |title=Rajinikanth 12.12.12: A Birthday Special |publisher=[[The Hindu|Kasturi & Sons Ltd]] |year=2012 |editor-la